                                                                                               INFORMED CONSENT FORM

Instructions:

The Title of this research study is, “A study to explore the relationship between a student athlete’s Courageous follower role and upward influence tactics.”

My name is Jeffrey Stewart, a doctoral student under the supervision of Dr. June Maul in the College of Doctoral Studies at Grand Canyon University. This study aims to determine if a student athlete's followership roles are related to the upward influence tactics, they use to influence coaches on a sports team at a college or university.

                                                                                                        KEY INFORMATION

• How do I know if I can be in this study?
    o You can take part in this study if you:
     o Are a full-time Student at a college or university in the United States
     o Are a Student Athlete at a college or university in the United States
     o Have been on a college or university sports team for more than 1 year.

    You cannot participate in this study if you:
     o Are currently suspended from taking part on the team or suspended at the College or University.

• What am I being asked to do? If you agree to be in this study, you will be asked to: Complete an online multiple – choice Questionnaire /Survey of 28 questions about your relationship with your coach. This survey will take between 30 – 40 minutes to complete.
     o Answer demographic questions related to number of years of participation as an athlete, age, gender, and race.
     o Answer questions relating to your role as a follower of the leader or you team (your coach).
     o Answer questions relating to how you influence your coach.
     o You can complete this survey:
          • On your own time.
          • On your own electronic device or computer.
     o Please allow enough time to complete the survey where there are no interruptions using a mobile device, tablet, or computer.

• Who will have access to my information?
     Myself, the dissertation chair, committee members, and all College of Doctoral Studies’ reviewers may view your information. There is no connection to your answers and your name.
     Participation is voluntary. You can leave the study at any time, even if you have not finished. If you decide to stop participation, you may do so by simply closing out of the browser. No information will be used unless the survey is completed in its entirety.

• Any possible risks or discomforts?
     You may experience discomfort or reluctance to answer questions regarding your relationship with your coach.
     o Your anonymity will be protected.

• Any direct benefits for me?
     o The results of the study may supply an understanding of the influence tactics an athlete uses to influence a coach.
• Any paid compensation or incentives for my time?
     o Participants will receive compensation per the Amazon Mechanical Turk terms Specific to this survey, which is $5.00.

• How will my information and/or identity be protected? I will not collect any identifiable information from you such as name, date of birth, address, etc. I will not be able to link participant data back to you. Your information and identity will be protected.
     o Data as well as any data analysis will be kept on a secure password-protected folder on an external hard drive at the researcher’s residence for three years. Data analyses will be conducted on a password protected computer.
     o The data will be stored for three years, after which it will be destroyed.
     o Only the researcher and committee team will have access to the data.


                                                                                                    PRESENTATION OF INFORMATION COLLECTED

The research data will be published in a final dissertation, per Grand Canyon University policy. In the future, it is possible the data will be presented at a conference or used in other published work.

The survey does not ask for any identifiable information. None of your personal information such as your name or address will be collected. Only the data associated with the survey answers will be collected by this researcher.

                                                                                                                                                                             Part 1 - The Followership Profile – 20 Questions:

Statement
1. I create a supportive environment on my sports team in which change can occur.
2. I am passionate about my work.
3. I acknowledge the improvements that my coach has made.
4. I provide support to my coach for experimentation and learning.
5. I prepare to transfer responsibilities should severance become necessary.
6. I am self-managed in meeting deadlines and keeping commitments.
7. I reflect my coaches values to the team without injecting my own personal agenda.
8. I assume responsibility in dilemmas where rules impede service.
9. I would quite the team to protect my coach from the repercussions of my actions.
10. I establish coping mechanisms that reinforce transformational progress.
11. I summarize communications for my coach.
12. I minimize unnecessary pressure on my coach.
13. I defend my coach from unwarranted attacks.
14. I encourage complainers to communicate concerns not emotions.
15. confront groupthink.
16. I assess my own performance.
17. I take initiative without formal authority.
18. I challenge inappropriate behaviors.
19. I am willing to bend the rules to get the right things done.
20. I will not compromise my personal ethics for continued employment.

                                                                                                                                                                             Part 2 – Influence Tactics used on my Coach. 18 Questions:

Statement
1. I act very humble to him/her while making my request.
2. I act in a friendly manner prior to asking for what I want.
3. I make him/her feel good about me before making my request.
4. I remind him/her of past favors that I did for him/her.
5. I offered an exchange (e.g. if you do this for me, I will do something for you.
6. I offered to make a personal sacrifice if he/she would do what I wanted (e.g. work late, work harder, do his/her share of the work,..etc.)
7. I use logic to convince him/her.
8. I explain the reasons for my request.
9. I present him/her with information in support of my point of view.
10. I had a shutdown in which I confronted him/her face-to-face.
11. I expressed my anger verbally.

12. I used a forceful manner; I tried things such as demands, the setting of deadlines, and the expression of strong emotions.
13. I obtained the informal support of higher ups.
14. I made a formal appeal to higher levels to back up my request.
15. I relied on the chain of command on people higher up in the organization who have power over him/her.
16. I obtained the support of co-workers (teammates) to back up my request.
17. I obtained the support of my subordinates (teammates) to back up my request.
18. I mobilized other people in the organization to help me in influencing him/her.
